[5] Germany update
Date: Tue 31 Jan 2012
Source: FLI (Federal Research Institute for Animal Health, Riems, Germany) [summ., edited]
http://www.fli.bund.de/en/startseite/current-news/animal-disease-situation/new-orthobunyavirus-detected-in-cattle-in-germany.html


Current information on SBV, last updated 31 Jan 2012
----------------------------------------------------
In Germany, animals from 186 holdings have, so far, tested positive for SBV. The cases occurred in 7 cattle holdings, 172 sheep holdings, and 7 goat holdings. Affected federal states are North Rhine-Westphalia (5 cattle, 104 sheep, 3 goat holdings), Lower Saxony (1 cattle, 35 sheep, 2 goat holdings), Hesse (12 sheep, 1 goat holdings), Rhineland-Palatinate (1 bison, 2 sheep holdings), Baden-Wuerttemberg (1 goat holding), Brandenburg (3 sheep holdings), and Thuringia (1 sheep holding) [see map at http://www.fli.bund.de/fileadmin/dam_uploads/tierseuchen/Schmallenberg_Virus/Karten/Map_Schmallenberg_20120131.jpg].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Maps of Germany can be seen at http://healthmap.org/r/1zJl and http://faculty.bemidjistate.edu/ckippenhan/MoreAboutMe/images/5e25ddf758.jpg. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]

[Akabane disease, which closely resembles SBV, has been regarded as a disease of ruminant embryos; the virus may kill the embryo (resulting, during early pregnancy, in its unnoticed resorption or, if the infection occurs during later stages, in abortion). In case the embryo survives, grosso modo its systems, which are in their most active developmental stages during the viraemia, are the ones liable to be affected. These are primarily the CNS system in early pregnancy and the muscle/skeleton in later stages (leading to arthrogryposis and other skeletal system malformations). The changes first become apparent during or following birth.

The 1st scientific paper on SBV has now become available as an "Ahead of Print/In Press Dispatch":
B Hoffmann, M Scheuch, D Hoeper, R Jungblut, et al: Novel _Orthobunyavirus_ in Cattle, Europe, 2011. Emerg Infect Dis. 2012 March; 18(3).

Abstract
"In 2011, an unidentified disease in cattle was reported in Germany and the Netherlands. Clinical signs included fever, decreased milk production, and diarrhea. Metagenomic analysis identified a novel orthobunyavirus, which subsequently was isolated from blood of affected animals. Surveillance was initiated to test malformed newborn animals in the affected region."

The paper, including a dendrogram and the results of 3 experimentally infected calves, is available at http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/18/3/11-1905_article.htm. - Mod.AS]
